import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['job'] = data['job'].astype('category')
    data['sex'] = data['sex'].astype('category')
    data = data.groupby(['job', 'sex']).sum().reset_index()
    data = data.sort_values(by=['count'], ascending=False)
    data = data.groupby('job').head(2)
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    ax = plt.subplot(111)
    ax.bar(data[data['sex'] == 'men']['job'], data[data['sex'] == 'men']['count'], width=0.4, color='b', align='center')
    ax.bar(data[data['sex'] == 'women']['job'], data[data['sex'] == 'women']['count'], width=0.4, color='r', align='center')
    ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    plt.title('What is the most common job among men and women?', wrap=True)
    return plt

chart = plot(data)

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['year'], format='%Y', errors='ignore')
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    jobs = data['job'].unique()
    for job in jobs:
        job_data = data[data['job'] == job]
        plt.plot(job_data['year'], job_data['count'], label=job)
    plt.title('How has the distribution of jobs changed over time?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Year')
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.legend(loc='upper left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    else:
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    return plt

chart = plot(data)

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['year'], format='%Y', errors='ignore')
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    jobs = data['job'].unique()
    men_counts = []
    women_counts = []
    for job in jobs:
        men_count = data[(data['job'] == job) & (data['sex'] == 'men')]['count'].sum()
        women_count = data[(data['job'] == job) & (data['sex'] == 'women')]['count'].sum()
        men_counts.append(men_count)
        women_counts.append(women_count)
    x = range(len(jobs))
    plt.bar(x, men_counts, label='Men')
    plt.bar(x, women_counts, bottom=men_counts, label='Women')
    plt.xticks(x, jobs, rotation=90 if len(jobs) > 20 else 0)
    if len(jobs) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('What is the gender distribution for each job?', wrap=True)
    return plt

chart = plot(data)

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['perc'] = pd.to_numeric(data['perc'], errors='coerce')
    data = data.dropna(subset=['perc'])
    jobs = data['job'].unique()
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(jobs), figsize=(6, 6), sharex=True, sharey=True)
    fig.suptitle('What is the distribution of percentages for each job?')
    for i, job in enumerate(jobs):
        job_data = data[data['job'] == job]
        axs[i].hist(job_data['perc'], bins=20)
        axs[i].set_title(job)
        axs[i].xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
        axs[i].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=90)
    plt.tight_layout()
    return plt

chart = plot(data)

    plt.bar(data['job'], data['count'], label='Count')

    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('What is the average count and percentage for each job?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
